# Logz.io Real User Monitoring Repository Guidelines (Condensed)

## 1) Engineering Philosophy

- Invisible operation: do not impact host app behavior or performance
- No-throw policy: never throw in runtime paths; log and continue
- Graceful degradation: recover safely on failures (network/exporter)
- Clean integration: prefer OTEL instrumentations over custom code
- Privacy: do not collect PII; document collected fields

## 2) Supported Environments

- Browsers (broad support). Feature-detect APIs and guard for missing ones
- Tests: Node.js + Jest (ts-jest) + Playwright for browser tests
- TypeScript strict mode

## 3) Project Structure (essential)

```
src/
├─ openTelemetry/     # providers (logs/metrics/traces), processors, setup
├─ instrumentation/   # instrumentations & trackers
├─ context/           # session + view management
├─ config/            # config types + defaults
├─ shared/            # logger, constants, event listener
├─ utils/             # env collection, helpers, store
└─ aggregations/      # web vitals aggregator

tests/
├─ unit/              # unit tests for prod code
├─ integration/       # JSDOM behavior-only integration
└─ browser/           # Playwright full browser tests
```

## 4) Coding Conventions

- Naming: variables camelCase; functions camelCase verbs; classes PascalCase; constants SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE
- Imports: ESM only; external before internal
- TypeScript: strong typing, no `any`; use interfaces/guards; document complex types briefly
- Structure: early returns; keep functions focused (<50 lines ideal); no empty catch blocks; comments explain "why"

## 5) Error Handling & Logging

- Runtime: do not throw; log via `RUMLogger`
- Levels: error | warn | info (default) | debug
- Log when: feature enable/disable; setup/validation errors; exporter failures; useful debug
- Initialization: guard provider/exporter creation & registration; on critical init failure log error and cancel init (don’t start session/instrumentations)
- Shutdown/forceFlush: must not throw

## 6) OpenTelemetry Conventions

- Providers: separate logs, metrics, traces; use OTLP exporters
- Processors: enrich with session/view context; frustration metrics where enabled
- Samplers: configurable sampling rate
- Semantic attributes: use constants (e.g., `ATTR_SESSION_ID`, `ATTR_VIEW_ID`); prefix Logz.io attrs: `logzio.*`
- Resources: include `service.name`, `service.version`, region/token, and environment data (browser/OS/device/language)

## 7) Configuration (RUMConfig)

- tokens: `{ traces, metrics, logs }`
- enable: flags: `userActions`, `navigation`, `documentLoad`, `resourceLoad`, `consoleLogs`, `errorTracking`, `webVitals`, `viewEvents`, `frustrationDetection`
- service: `{ name, version }`
- region: Logz.io region
- samplingRate: 0–100
- environmentData: flags to collect OS, browser, device, language
- frustrationThresholds: `{ rageClickCount, rageClickIntervalMs, heavyLoadThresholdMs }`
- Defaults in `src/config/defaults.ts`
- Validation:
  - If metrics token missing and metrics-dependent features enabled → warn and auto-disable metrics-dependent features
  - If logs token missing and logs-dependent features enabled → warn and auto-disable logs-dependent features

## 8) Session & View Lifecycle (key rules)

- Persisted keys: `logzio-rum-session-id` and `logzio-rum-last-activity` in localStorage
- `start()` initializes session (existing or new), sets timers, starts view, updates last activity
- `end()` ends view, flushes, clears timers; does NOT clear persisted session keys
- `shutdown()` calls `end()`, removes listeners, and clears both persisted keys (fresh start next time)
- beforeunload: `end()` only (do NOT clear session key; other tabs may still be active)
- storage events: if session id removed → end; if session id changed → end + renew with new id
- inactivity: timeout clears session id; max-duration triggers renewal

## 9) Testing Strategy (3-tier)

1) Unit (Jest + ts-jest)
- Scope: production code (config, providers, processors, samplers, instrumentations, session/view)
- Use centralized mocks in `tests/unit/__utils__/`
- Behavior-first, no-throw verification, attribute/resource correctness
- Coverage >= 80%

2) Integration (JSDOM behavior-only)
- Scope: `LogzioRUM.init()` flow, registration, console/navigation/interactions/errors
- Avoid OTLP exporters; disable `webVitals`, `viewEvents`, `frustrationDetection` to keep JSDOM stable
- Keep tests deterministic and warning-free

3) Browser (Playwright)
- Scope: real browser APIs (DOM events, History API, PerformanceObserver), frustration detection, network
- Verify interactions/navigation/network/console/errors and metrics
- Use test server and mock collector where needed; assert session/view attributes and telemetry shape

### Mocking & Helpers (unit)
- Prefer shared helpers in `tests/unit/__utils__/` (loggerMocks, utilsMocks, otelApiMocks, etc.)
- Use factory `jest.mock` pattern, place before imports; prefer real constants; avoid inline ad‑hoc mocks

### Quality Bar
- Behavior-first tests; avoid implementation-detail assertions where possible
- Consolidate scenarios with `it.each` when appropriate
- Reset singletons/localStorage between tests; maintain deterministic conditions

## 10) Performance Guidelines

- Bundle: minimize deps; tree-shakeable patterns
- Runtime: minimize sync work; use `requestIdleCallback` for non-critical work; batch exporter operations; clean up listeners/timers

## 11) Release & CI (condensed)

- SemVer; update `CHANGELOG.md`
- Pre-publish: `npm run lint`, `npm run format`, `npm run test` (green, coverage met)
- CI: enforce tests, lint, coverage, and basic bundle-size checks
- Commits: descriptive with rationale; reference issues when relevant

## 12) Documentation

- README: install, usage, config, advanced usage, troubleshooting
- Code: JSDoc for public APIs; brief comments for non-obvious logic

## 13) Security & Compliance

- Do not collect sensitive inputs; scrub where necessary
- Respect privacy settings and feature-detect APIs
- Never modify globals unexpectedly; guard and handle unsupported APIs

## 14) Runtime Safety Checklist

- [ ] Init guards around provider/exporter construction & registration
- [ ] Auto-disable dependent features when tokens missing (with warnings)
- [ ] Runtime log paths never throw; shutdown/forceFlush are safe
- [ ] Listeners/timers cleaned up on `shutdown()`
- [ ] Cross-tab storage events handled without throwing

## 15) Developer Workflow

- Branches: small, focused feature/bugfix
- Reviews: correctness, performance, maintainability, no-throw compliance, tests
- Keep PRs small; include rationale and tests

## Appendix: Project Overview & Quick Start

### Project Overview (short)
- A browser RUM SDK built on OpenTelemetry to collect traces/logs/metrics from real users and export via OTLP to Logz.io. The SDK is designed to be invisible and safe, enriching telemetry with session/view context while respecting privacy.

### Minimal Quick Start
```ts
import { LogzioRUM } from '@src';

LogzioRUM.init({
  region: 'us',
  tokens: { traces: 'TRACES_TOKEN', logs: 'LOGS_TOKEN' },
  service: { name: 'web-app', version: '1.0.0' },
  enable: {
    navigation: true,
    documentLoad: true,
    userActions: true,
    consoleLogs: true,
    errorTracking: true,
    frustrationDetection: true,
    webVitals: true,
    viewEvents: true,
    consoleLogs: true,
  }
});
```

### Core Attributes Cheat Sheet (common)
- Session: `session.id`
- View: `view.id`, `http.url`
- Network: `http.method`, `http.status_code`
- Interactions: `target.element`, `target.tagName`
- Frustration (when enabled): `frustration.type`
- Resource attributes (on all signals): `service.name`, `service.version`, `logzio.region`, `logzio.token`, environment data (browser/OS/device/language)

---
When in doubt, prioritize host app safety and telemetry quality. Keep it simple, predictable, and invisible.